  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: The Double Coat in the Tropics" imageAlt="German Shepherd having its double coat brushed with an undercoat rake" imageSrc={imgScene4} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Shepherd's double coat is a year-round commitment, and the breed's "German shedder" nickname is honestly earned. Brush 3 to 4 times a week with a proper undercoat rake, daily during the twice-yearly coat blows, and accept that the hair becomes a household fact of life. Baths every four to six weeks, with thorough drying, because a damp undercoat in tropical humidity is how hot spots start.</p>
      <p>And the rule we repeat on every double-coated page: never shave a Shepherd. The coat insulates against heat as well as cold, protects the skin from sun, and shaving wrecks how it grows back. Brush it, don't shave it.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="German Shepherd Health: What We Check and What to Watch" imageAlt="German Shepherd puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene5} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Shepherd goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The breed's health conversation centres on the joints: hip and elbow dysplasia are the well-known large-breed risks, so puppyhood is joint-protective by design — controlled growth feeding, no stair marathons, no forced running before maturity, and a lean weight for life. The other watch-point is the back end in older age; keeping your Shepherd lean and well-muscled through daily exercise is the single best protection there is.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple but breed-specific: your puppy comes with the large-breed food it is already eating, portioned for controlled growth, and any change should be gradual over a week. See the <a href="/learn/puppy-health/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your German Shepherd's First Week at Home" imageAlt="German Shepherd puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene6} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Shepherd explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person, including the large-breed feeding plan and a gentle first introduction to the leash and muzzle. Learn more about <a href="/delivery/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and joint-safe. A fixed feeding routine with measured portions, the toilet pads where we placed them, and play that stays on the floor, no leaping, no stairs, while those big-breed joints are growing.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and for this breed it is the most important week you'll spend. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer now: early socialisation, basic obedience and calm muzzle-wearing installed at eight kilos are a gift at thirty-five. See <a href="/free-training/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

